    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-12T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-12T05:00:00-05:00" n="279"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/10844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cole</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-12T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 12, 1941—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>192. Doolittle<note n="66" xml:id="d279fn66">Hooker A. Doolittle, Consul at
                        Tunis.</note> saw Colonel Truchet, many years French head Native Affairs
                    Tangier, now Weygand’s staff here, who returned from <pb facs="0344" n="332"
                        xml:id="pg_332"/> Vichy Friday. He developed same theme as Monick with one
                    important change.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Sole hope North Africa, American intervention with 500 tanks, 1,000 planes
                        and strong naval forces. However, no declaration should be made about our
                        interest in African coast until forces are ready to land as such declaration
                        would precipitate German action. German divisions now reported massing in
                        Pyrenees, presumably for move through Spain.</p>
                    <p>He also stated presence Abd-el Krim<note n="67" xml:id="d279fn67">Moroccan
                            Nationalist leader who led Riff uprising against Spain, 1920–24.</note>
                        in Fez would be worth two divisions against Spanish and further that French
                        Navy rapidly turning towards United States and like Army would gladly work
                        with us.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>On way from Morocco Doolittle learned new Germans there are settling in large
                    groups at Fedala, Port-Lyautey, Boulvant, all oil installations. He reports
                    Spanish friends informed him German action expected North Africa before end May.
                    If so, situation appears hopeless unless effective aid available now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cole</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
